SUMMARY:Experimental and Behavioural Economics Seminar Series – Anastasia
  Danilov (Humboldt University) – The Lifecycle of Affirmative Action Pol
 icies and Its Effect on Effort and Sabotage Behavior
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Anastasia Danilov: “The Lifecycle of Affirmative Action Polic
 ies and Its Effect on Effort and Sabotage Behavior”\nhttps://anastasiada
 nilov.de/\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82654401351?pwd=V6TMN2ZpNRILV
 KO2Y5za5S7GjfbAGG.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/Bir
 LkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nOne of the main goals of affirmative action (
 AA) policies is to enable disadvantaged groups to compete with their privi
 leged counterparts. Existing literature documents that AA can result in bo
 th more egalitarian outcomes and higher exerted efforts in competition. Ho
 wever\, the direct behavioral effects of the introduction and removal of s
 uch policies are still unexplored. It is also unclear how specific AA tool
 s\, such as head-start for a disadvantaged group or handicap for a privile
 ged group\, affect behavior. We investigate these aspects in a laboratory 
 experiment incorporating a real-effort tournament and sabotage. We find th
 at AA does not necessarily result in higher effort. High performers who ha
 ve already experienced an existing AA-free tournament reduce their effort 
 levels after the introduction of the AA policy. Additionally\, we observe 
 less sabotage under AA when the tournament begins directly under the AA re
 gime. The removal of AA policies\, however\, significantly intensifies sab
 otage. Overall\, there are no systematic differences between handicap and 
 head-start in terms of effort or sabotage.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82654401351?pwd=V6TMN2ZpNRILVKO2Y5za5S7GjfbAG
 G.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:d15f6afb753b8c9c854cea179bb2c479@generated
DTSTAMP:20260422T200022Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260422T200022Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260514T110000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260514T121500
SUMMARY:Experimental and Behavioural Economics Seminar Series – Elif Ince
 kara-Hafalir (UTS) – When Do You Expect to Be Paid? Expectations Shape P
 atience
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Elif Incekara-Hafalir: “When Do You Expect to Be Paid? Expect
 ations Shape Patience”\nhttps://sites.google.com/site/incekara/\n\nZoom:
  https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82654401351?pwd=V6TMN2ZpNRILVKO2Y5za5S7GjfbAGG.
 1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\n
 ABSTRACT:\nTime preferences shape decisions about saving\, education\, and
  health\, yet research has largely overlooked how expectations about payme
 nt timing influence elicited measures of time preferences. We provide caus
 al evidence that such expectations systematically affect intertemporal cho
 ices. In a pre-registered experiment\, we manipulate payment-timing expect
 ations while holding choice menus fixed. Participants expecting payment in
  the future choose more patient options than those expecting payment today
 \, despite identical rewards and delays. A reference-dependent model\, whe
 re expected timing serves as a temporal reference point\, explains these s
 hifts. The findings illuminate patterns in the time preference literature 
 and suggest a low-cost policy lever.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82654401351?pwd=V6TMN2ZpNRILVKO2Y5za5S7GjfbAG
 G.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
