SUMMARY:Econometrics – Timothy Neal (UNSW) – Instrument-Hacking
LOCATION:Room 404\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Timothy Neal: “Instrument-Hacking”\nhttps://sites.google.co
 m/site/tjrneal/\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82137514093?pwd=KSb1ZXI
 yCKxNbsIkrno9M8a3jpA8CY.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.
 gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nIn instrumental-variable (IV) studies\,
  researchers often evaluate multiple candidate instruments or first-stage 
 specifications and selectively report the one with the strongest first-sta
 ge F-statistic\, the largest second-stage t-statistic\, or a combination o
 f both. We show that this form of instrument selection (“instrument-hack
 ing”) induces median bias in conventional IV estimators toward the OLS e
 stimand\, and that the bias increases with the number of candidate instrum
 ents/specifications considered. In simulations calibrated to sample sizes 
 and first-stage strengths typical of IV studies published in leading econo
 mics journals\, the resulting median bias is economically meaningful even 
 when the researcher considers only a small set of candidates. We conclude 
 with practical recommendations for research design and reporting practices
  that reduce the scope for instrument-hacking and its consequences for inf
 erence.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82137514093?pwd=KSb1ZXIyCKxNbsIkrno9M8a3jpA8C
 Y.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
