SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Anthony Van Den Berg (University of Melbo
 urne) – Private Ambition\, Public Pressure: How Observability Determines
  Optimal Goal Design
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Anthony Van Den Berg: “Private Ambition\, Public Pressure: Ho
 w Observability Determines Optimal Goal Design”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://
 maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nHow do autonomy and observ
 ability shape the effectiveness of goals? This paper studies whether the p
 referred mode of goal setting in terms of motivating effort depends on whe
 ther goals and goal outcomes are private or public. A theoretical framewor
 k combining reference-dependent preferences and social image concerns pred
 icts that externally set goals outperform self-set goals when private\, bu
 t that public observability can reverse this ranking. These predictions ar
 e tested in a laboratory experiment\, in which participants complete real-
 effort tasks over multiple sessions and can set or receive a performance-b
 ased goal for their future selves. In a 2×2 design\, goals are either sel
 f-set or externally assigned\, and outcomes are either private or publicly
  disclosed through a leaderboard. The results inform how policymakers can 
 utilize observability for optimal goal designs
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:5d5bdb5f9a3cad9cbc282cedc344bbf6@generated
DTSTAMP:20260422T200022Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260422T200022Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260417T141000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260417T145000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Charon Yang (University of Melbourne) –
  Apps Matter: Search Dynamics and Platform Design
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Charon Yang: “Apps Matter: Search Dynamics and Platform Desig
 n”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT
 :\nThis paper studies how search platform design shapes consumer search be
 havior. We develop a stylised model in which a mobile app lowers search co
 sts and introduces asymmetric push notifications for price decreases\, imp
 lying higher overall search and\, if push effects dominate\, weaker search
  asymmetry. We test these predictions using FuelCheck in New South Wales\,
  Australia\, combining daily station-level price data with the universe of
  individual-level searches from 2016 to 2019. Under web-based search\, usa
 ge responds temporarily to price shocks and is asymmetric\, with consumers
  searching more after price increases than after price decreases. After th
 e app launch\, search becomes higher and more persistent\, but asymmetry d
 oes not significantly decline. The evidence suggests that the app changed 
 the technology of monitoring without generating a dominant directional pus
 h effect\, likely because of design frictions. More broadly\, the results 
 show that the effectiveness of transparency policies depends not only on d
 isclosure\, but also on platform design.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:252f99fb641eabb9c5ffc4f162740858@generated
DTSTAMP:20260422T200022Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260422T200022Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260417T145000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260417T153000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Lindsay Robinson (University of Melbourne
 ) – Autonomous Algorithmic Collusion: Efficient Learning with Q-Function
  Approximation
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Lindsay Robinson: “Autonomous Algorithmic Collusion: Efficien
 t Learning with Q-Function Approximation”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.a
 pp.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nAutonomous algorithmic collusion
  occurs when firms delegate to autonomous algorithms that learn to collude
  with each other through repeated interaction.  In this paper\, I show how
  efficient learning algorithms can dramatically increase the speed and per
 fection of autonomous algorithmic collusion.  I consider Q-learning pricin
 g algorithms with a parsimonious Q-function that scales linearly in the di
 mension of the state representation.  This allows the algorithms to condit
 ion on a higher dimensional representation of the price history\, and to b
 etter distinguish between temporary and sustained competitor deviation fro
 m collusive prices.  The algorithms can coordinate quickly on symmetric jo
 int-profit-maximizing collusive prices in a repeated simultaneous oligopol
 y pricing game.  I explore the robustness of collusive prices to the algor
 ithms’ parametrization and the strategic environment\, and conclude with
  implications for competition policy.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:e261f2e466f80bd7f59e074dea7004ff@generated
DTSTAMP:20260422T200022Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260422T200022Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260424T133000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260424T141000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Annik Ketterle (University of Melbourne) 
 – Central Bank Transfers and Sovereign Risk
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Annik Ketterle: “Central Bank Transfers and Sovereign Risk”
 \n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nE
 merging market sovereign spreads often remain elevated even when consolida
 ted public sector balance sheets appear sound. I argue that institutional 
 separation between central banks and treasuries — specifically\, the rul
 es governing transfers of foreign-currency reserve revaluation gains — g
 enerates competing effects on sovereign borrowing costs that the consolida
 ted position obscures.\n\nIn a New Keynesian sovereign default model\, a t
 ransfer rule parameterised by α ∈ [0\,1] governs the treasury's access 
 to central bank revaluation gains. Lower α reduces fiscal capacity during
  depreciations — precisely when default risk is elevated — but discipl
 ines government borrowing ex ante. The net effect is ambiguous: the relati
 onship between α and the equilibrium default probability may be non-monot
 onic\, with an interior α* ∈ (0\,1) that reduces sovereign risk below t
 he fully consolidated benchmark.\n\nThe findings speak to ongoing policy d
 ebates — from South Africa's contested Reserve Bank transfers to Argenti
 na's repeated raids on central bank reserves — suggesting that the insti
 tutional design governing central bank transfers involves a fundamental te
 nsion between fiscal insurance and borrowing discipline.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:532b638e82c42feee32fb825fd8b2ab8@generated
DTSTAMP:20260422T200022Z
